  "chunk_index": 35,
  "summary": "Following his discussion with Hakast regarding a letter from Melina Rivale and the confirmation of a scar on a deceased man's ear, Colin Lamb visits Mrs. Lamech at 62 Wilbraham Crescent. Lamb clarifies that he is not a detective investigating the recent phone booth murder, but is instead conducting his own investigation into her husband, Michel.\n\nMrs. Lamech reveals that Michel plans to move to Moscow, a decision she does not fully support because of her moderate leftist views and her desire to raise their children as British. While she expresses uncertainty regarding whether Michel is involved in the Larkin case, she remains vague about his specific plans. She mentions her intention to find work, possibly in secretarial duties, though Lamb warns her against working at Cavendish Typewriting and Stenography due to the misfortune affecting its employees.\n\nAs Lamb leaves, he encounters Mrs. McNaughton, who is carrying a heavy shopping bag. After helping her to her kitchen, Lamb discovers that the bag, which she claimed contained cornflakes and watermelon, actually contains three bottles of whiskey. He concludes that this explains her unsteady gait and cheerful demeanor. Finally, while walking toward Albany Road, Lamb meets Mr. Brand, who inquires about the progress of the Rivale case and the identification of the body.",
